===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|scarlet}}, {{m|enm|scarlat}}, borrowed from {{der|en|fro|escarlate||a type of cloth}}, from {{der|en|ML.|scarlatum|t=scarlet cloth}}. This was long thought to derive from {{der|en|fa|سقرلات|tr=saqerlât||a warm woollen cloth}}, but the Persian word (first attested in the 1290s) is now thought to be from {{der|en|ar|سِقِلَّات}}, denoting very expensive, luxury silks dyed scarlet-red using the exceptionally expensive dye, first attested around the ninth century. The origin of the word ''siqillāt'' is itself uncertain and may come from the Late Roman term ''sigillatus'' (Latin)/''σιγιλλατον'' (Greek), denoting a kind of cloth decorated with patterns (from Latin ''sigillum'' 'seal'). The word then came to be used of woollen cloth dyed with the same dye. The most obvious route for the Arabic word ''siqillāt'' to have entered the Romance languages would be via the Arabic-speaking Iberian region of [[Al-Andalus]], particularly [[Almería]], where kermes was produced extensively.<ref>John Munro, “[http://dx.doi.org/10.1163/2213-2139_emdt_COM_550|Scarlet]”, in ''Encyclopaedia of Medieval Dress and Textiles of the British Isles c. 450-1450'', ed. by Gale Owen-Crocker, Elizabeth Coatsworth and Maria Hayward (Leiden: Brill, 2012).</ref>

